The paper discusses a statistical analysis of highly-cited papers published in different cities around the world, using Web of Science data. The approach is more analytically oriented and allows for the assessment of observed versus expected numbers of excellent papers for a city. While the paper does not explicitly mention computer science, the methodology and data analysis techniques used are relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, such as digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), social and information networks (cs.SI), cybernetics (cs.CY), and software engineering (cs.SD).
